{"title_page": "Adrian Beecroft", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name           = Adrian Beecroft\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| birth_date     = 20 May 1947\n| birth_place    = [[Yorkshire]], [[England]]\n| death_place    =\n| education      = [[Hymers College]]<br/>[[Queen's College, Oxford]]<br/>[[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation     = [[Angel investor]]\n| spouse         = Jacqueline Beecroft\n| home_town      = [[London]] and [[Oxford]], England\n| children       =\n}}\n\n'''Paul Adrian Barlow Beecroft''' (born [[Yorkshire]], 20 May 1947<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=JiyMi1qc8tMfb1IhqEwzeQ&scan=1|title=Index entry |accessdate=25 May 2012 |work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref>) is a [[British People|British]] [[venture capitalist]] based in [[London]]. He was for many years [[Chief Investment Officer]] of the [[private equity]] group [[Apax]]. He was until recently [[Chairman]] of Dawn Capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawncapital.co.uk/ |title=Home |publisher=Dawn Capital |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Apax veteran Beecroft returns to VC roots|work=Financial News|date=25 May 2010|url=http://www.efinancialnews.com/story/2010-05-25/adrian-beecroft-dawn-capital}}</ref>\n\nAmong the companies in which Beecroft has personally invested are [[Mimecast]] and Insignis.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\nBeecroft has donated more than \u00a3500,000 to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] since 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Beecroft proposals: how Tory donor's radical blueprint split the government|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=23 May 2012|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/23/beecroft-proposals-coalition-support-criticism|location=UK}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAdrian Beecroft was born and raised in [[Yorkshire]]. He studied at [[Hymers College]] in [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3664641/The-New-Philanthropists.html|title=The New Philanthropists|last=Thomas|first=David|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2007-04-20|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from [[Queen's College, Oxford]] with a first class honours degree in [[Physics]] in 1968 and is now an Honorary Fellow of the College.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=85311&privcapId=35903973|title=Profile: Adrian Beecroft|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>  In 1976 he gained a M.B.A from Harvard Business School, where he studied as a [[Harkness Fellowship|Harkness Fellow]].<ref name=\":0\" />  He graduated from Harvard as a [[Baker scholar|Baker Scholar]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Career==\nAdrian Beecroft has an extensive career in venture capital and private equity, specialising in IT investments.<ref name=\":0\" />  He was the Chairman of the [[British Venture Capital Association]] in 1991.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/business-big-shot-adrian-beecroft-032nzk2kkxq|title=Business big shot: Adrian Beecroft|date=2010-05-25|work=The Times|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nBeecroft started his career at [[International Computers Limited|ICL]], in the computer industry.<ref name=\":1\" />  In 1973, he moved to Ocean Transport and Trading Ltd., working to develop their new business area of bulk shipping.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter graduating from [[Harvard Business School]], he joined [[Boston Consulting Group]] in [[London]]. He became Vice President of BCG in 1982.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1984, Beecroft joined Apax Partners, and was there for 25 years until he retired from his role as [[Chief investment officer|Chief Investment Officer]] in 2008.<ref name=\":1\" /> While working at Apax, he served as their representative on the boards of over 20 public and private companies, including [[Computacenter]], Alkane Energy and [[Healthcare at Home]]. He played a significant part in the international expansion of the business, which now has over $20 billion under management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/person/adrian-beecroft|title=Adrian Beecroft|website=Crunchbase|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2006, Beecroft was appointed to the [[NESTA]] Investment Committee.<ref>http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/hc0607/hc06/0654/0654.pdf</ref> At that time NESTA was still a [[QUANGO]].\n\nBeecroft was awarded the BVCA's Hall of Fame honour at the Private Equity Awards in 2009.<ref name=\":0\" />  He was a member of [[Sir David Walker|Sir David Walker's]] committee on improving the transparency of the private equity industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2007/03/21/3305/walker-assembles-high-flying-private-equity-working-group/|title=Walker Assembles High Flying Private Equity Working Group|website=ftalphaville.ft.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Beecroft joined Dawn Capital as the Chairman of their board.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Beecroft Report and controversy==\nOn 21 May 2012, the [[Beecroft Report]] caused considerable controversy in the UK due to its recommendations to relax regulation surrounding the dismissal of employees. The report claimed this would help to boost the economy.<ref>{{cite news|title=How Adrian Beecroft proposed to rip up decades of employee rights to boost the economy|author=Daily Telegraph|date=21 May 2012|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9275558/Analysis-How-Adrian-Beecroft-proposed-to-rip-up-decades-of-employee-rights-to-boost-the-economy.html|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> It was alleged that significant sections of the report had been doctored.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|title=Controversial Beecroft report on employment reform doctored by No 10|author=Daily Telegraph|date=21 May 2012|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9281161/Controversial-Beecroft-report-on-employment-reform-doctored-by-No-10.html|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> It was also reported that some recommendations had been removed from the original draft of the report.<ref name=\":2\" /> On 21 May [[Secretary of State for Business]] [[Vince Cable]] condemned the report, saying it was unnecessary for the government to scare workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18155827 |title=BBC News - Adrian Beecroft work report not doctored, No 10 says |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= 2012-05-22|accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> Beecroft responded by accusing Cable of being a socialist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9283748/Socialist-Vince-Cable-not-fit-for-office-says-Adrian-Beecroft.html|title='Socialist' Vince Cable not fit for office, says Adrian Beecroft|last=Winnett|first=Robert|date=2012-05-22|access-date=2018-09-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He referenced his own experience of having to pay \u00a3150,000 for unfairly dismissing an HR employee as one of the many reasons behind the recommendation in the report.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9283748/Socialist-Vince-Cable-not-fit-for-office-says-Adrian-Beecroft.html |title='Socialist' Vince Cable not fit for office, says Adrian Beecroft |publisher=Telegraph |date=2011-05-31 |accessdate=2012-05-22 |location=London |first=Robert |last=Winnett}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\n[[File:Beecroft Bldg Oxford.jpg|thumb|The Beecroft Building viewed from [[Parks Road]], [[Oxford]], completed in 2018]]\n\nBeecroft helped to found and funds the Beecroft Institute of Particle Physics and Cosmology (BIPAC)<ref name=\":3\" /> at [[Oxford University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.physics.ox.ac.uk/astro/bipac/ |title=Beecroft Institute of Particle Astrophysics and Cosmology |publisher=Physics.ox.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> He has also part-funded the [[Beecroft Building]], part of the [[Department of Physics, University of Oxford|Department of Physics]] in Oxford. This new building is specifically focused on [[Theoretical physics|theoretical]], [[Condensed matter physics|condensed matter]] and [[Quantum (physics)|quantum]] physics. According to ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', the funding for this building was inspired by Beecroft's interest in [[astrophysics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campaign.ox.ac.uk/news/beecroft-building|title=Celebrating the \u2018bottoming out\u2019 of Oxford\u2019s Beecroft Building|website=www.campaign.ox.ac.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nBeecroft has supported his school, Hymer's College in Hull.<ref name=\":3\" />  He has also been a Trustee of Impetus Trust, a social impact charity.<ref name=\":3\" /> Beecroft was also for six years the Chairman of the Cricket Foundation, now known as [[Chance to Shine]], a charity focused on bringing cricket back into British state school education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chancetoshine.org/news/cricket-foundation-elects-donald-brydon-as-new-chairman-of-the-board-of-trustees|title=Cricket Foundation elects Donald Brydon as new Chairman of the Board of Trustees|website=www.chancetoshine.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\nThrough the Beecroft Trust, Adrian and his wife sponsor the [[Oxford Academy, Oxfordshire|Oxford Academy]], an Academy school serving a very deprived area of Oxford.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theoxfordacademy.org.uk/Sponsors|title=Sponsors|website=www.theoxfordacademy.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> Since becoming an Academy school in 2010, its results have improved dramatically from 14% of the students achieving five A* to C grades including English and Maths to 56% achieving this in 2017. However, in 2019 only 17% of pupils achieved grade 5 or above at GCSE and the school had the worst Attainment 8 and Progress 8 scores of any mainstream school in Oxfordshire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/17988398.gcse-2019-results-oxford-academy-disappointed/|title=School 'disappointed' to come bottom in GCSE rankings|website=Oxford Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> In December 2019 the Head and governing body were removed after an [[Ofsted|OFSTED]] inspection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/18090495.head-governors-leave-oxford-academy-ofsted/|title=Mum says school is 'like juvey' as head and governors leave|website=Oxford Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\nMr Beecroft has also supported the [[UNESCO]] initiative to preserve the [[Belize Barrier Reef]] Reserve System, which was classified as in danger on the UNESCO List of World Heritage in Danger in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/1839/|title=Landmark Conservation Action leads to Belize Barrier Reef removal from List of World Heritage in Danger|last=Centre|first=UNESCO World Heritage|website=whc.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>  As of June 2018, the [[World Heritage Committee]] decided to remove the Belize Barrier Reef, which is the world's second largest coral reef, from the list.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-44627719|title=Belize reef taken off 'in danger' list|date=2018-06-27|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Aston Martin DBR1 Adrian Beecroft.jpg|thumb|Adrian Beecroft in his [[Aston Martin DBR1]]]]\nBeecroft lives in [[London]] and supports [[Lord's|Lord's Cricket Ground]] as a [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC) Trustee.<ref name=\":4\">{{Citation|last=Lord's Cricket Ground|title=Meet MCC Trustee Adrian Beecroft {{!}} MCC/Lord's|date=2015-09-29|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QqN_NLDNxVw|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>  As a trustee one of his core roles is assisting with the appointment of the Chairman, but also overseeing the wellbeing of the club and cricket ground.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lords.org/mcc/the-club/mcc-committee/|title=MCC Committee|website=www.lords.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> His enthusiasm for the sport came from watching the [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire County team]] play in Hull.<ref name=\":4\" />  He is the President of Cropredy Cricket Club for whom he still plays league cricket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cropredycc.play-cricket.com/website/player_stats_widget/batting_stats/142168|title=Cropredy CC|website=cropredycc.play-cricket.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\nBeecroft is a supporter of the [[North Yorkshire Moors Railway]] of which he is a Vice-President. He is a keen auto-enthusiast, having an extensive collection of vehicles, including several [[Aston Martin]]s, most notably a [[Aston Martin DBR1|DBR1]] which he races at a number of motoring events and later crashed in 2015.<ref>http://carbuzz.com/m/Article.aspx?Id=29621</ref> He is a governor of [[Hymers College]] in Hull.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat inline|Adrian Beecroft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beecroft, Adrian}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hymers College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The Queen's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Harkness Fellows]]\n[[Category:Angel investors]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name           = Adrian Beecroft\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| birth_date     = 20 May 1947\n| birth_place    = [[Yorkshire]], [[England]]\n| death_place    =\n| education      = [[Hymers College]]<br/>[[Queen's College, Oxford]]<br/>[[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation     = [[Angel investor]]\n| spouse         = Jacqueline Beecroft\n| home_town      = [[London]] and [[Oxford]], England\n| children       =\n}}\n\n'''Paul Adrian Barlow Beecroft''' (born [[Yorkshire]], 20 May 1947<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=JiyMi1qc8tMfb1IhqEwzeQ&scan=1|title=Index entry |accessdate=25 May 2012 |work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref>) is a [[British People|British]] [[venture capitalist]] based in [[London]]. He was for many years [[Chief Investment Officer]] of the [[private equity]] group [[Apax]]. He was until recently [[Chairman]] of Dawn Capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawncapital.co.uk/ |title=Home |publisher=Dawn Capital |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Apax veteran Beecroft returns to VC roots|work=Financial News|date=25 May 2010|url=http://www.efinancialnews.com/story/2010-05-25/adrian-beecroft-dawn-capital}}</ref>\n\nAmong the companies in which Beecroft has personally invested are [[Mimecast]] and Insignis.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\nBeecroft has donated more than \u00a3500,000 to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] since 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Beecroft proposals: how Tory donor's radical blueprint split the government|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=23 May 2012|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/23/beecroft-proposals-coalition-support-criticism|location=UK}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAdrian Beecroft was born and raised in [[Yorkshire]]. He studied at [[Hymers College]] in [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3664641/The-New-Philanthropists.html|title=The New Philanthropists|last=Thomas|first=David|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2007-04-20|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from [[Queen's College, Oxford]] with a first class honours degree in [[Physics]] in 1968 and is now an Honorary Fellow of the College.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=85311&privcapId=35903973|title=Profile: Adrian Beecroft|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>  In 1976 he gained a M.B.A from Harvard Business School, where he studied as a [[Harkness Fellowship|Harkness Fellow]].<ref name=\":0\" />  He graduated from Harvard as a [[Baker scholar|Baker Scholar]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Career==\nAdrian Beecroft has an extensive career in venture capital and private equity, specialising in IT investments.<ref name=\":0\" />  He was the Chairman of the [[British Venture Capital Association]] in 1991.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/business-big-shot-adrian-beecroft-032nzk2kkxq|title=Business big shot: Adrian Beecroft|date=2010-05-25|work=The Times|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nBeecroft started his career at [[International Computers Limited|ICL]], in the computer industry.<ref name=\":1\" />  In 1973, he moved to Ocean Transport and Trading Ltd., working to develop their new business area of bulk shipping.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter graduating from [[Harvard Business School]], he joined [[Boston Consulting Group]] in [[London]]. He became Vice President of BCG in 1982.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1984, Beecroft joined Apax Partners, and was there for 25 years until he retired from his role as [[Chief investment officer|Chief Investment Officer]] in 2008.<ref name=\":1\" /> While working at Apax, he served as their representative on the boards of over 20 public and private companies, including [[Computacenter]], Alkane Energy and [[Healthcare at Home]]. He played a significant part in the international expansion of the business, which now has over $20 billion under management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/person/adrian-beecroft|title=Adrian Beecroft|website=Crunchbase|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2006, Beecroft was appointed to the [[NESTA]] Investment Committee.<ref>http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/hc0607/hc06/0654/0654.pdf</ref> At that time NESTA was still a [[QUANGO]].\n\nBeecroft was awarded the BVCA's Hall of Fame honour at the Private Equity Awards in 2009.<ref name=\":0\" />  He was a member of [[Sir David Walker|Sir David Walker's]] committee on improving the transparency of the private equity industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2007/03/21/3305/walker-assembles-high-flying-private-equity-working-group/|title=Walker Assembles High Flying Private Equity Working Group|website=ftalphaville.ft.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Beecroft joined Dawn Capital as the Chairman of their board.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Beecroft Report and controversy==\nOn 21 May 2012, the [[Beecroft Report]] caused considerable controversy in the UK due to its recommendations to relax regulation surrounding the dismissal of employees. The report claimed this would help to boost the economy.<ref>{{cite news|title=How Adrian Beecroft proposed to rip up decades of employee rights to boost the economy|author=Daily Telegraph|date=21 May 2012|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9275558/Analysis-How-Adrian-Beecroft-proposed-to-rip-up-decades-of-employee-rights-to-boost-the-economy.html|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> It was alleged that significant sections of the report had been doctored.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|title=Controversial Beecroft report on employment reform doctored by No 10|author=Daily Telegraph|date=21 May 2012|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9281161/Controversial-Beecroft-report-on-employment-reform-doctored-by-No-10.html|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> It was also reported that some recommendations had been removed from the original draft of the report.<ref name=\":2\" /> On 21 May [[Secretary of State for Business]] [[Vince Cable]] condemned the report, saying it was unnecessary for the government to scare workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18155827 |title=BBC News - Adrian Beecroft work report not doctored, No 10 says |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= 2012-05-22|accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> Beecroft responded by accusing Cable of being a socialist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9283748/Socialist-Vince-Cable-not-fit-for-office-says-Adrian-Beecroft.html|title='Socialist' Vince Cable not fit for office, says Adrian Beecroft|last=Winnett|first=Robert|date=2012-05-22|access-date=2018-09-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He referenced his own experience of having to pay \u00a3150,000 for unfairly dismissing an HR employee as one of the many reasons behind the recommendation in the report.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9283748/Socialist-Vince-Cable-not-fit-for-office-says-Adrian-Beecroft.html |title='Socialist' Vince Cable not fit for office, says Adrian Beecroft |publisher=Telegraph |date=2011-05-31 |accessdate=2012-05-22 |location=London |first=Robert |last=Winnett}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\n[[File:Beecroft Bldg Oxford.jpg|thumb|The Beecroft Building viewed from [[Parks Road]], [[Oxford]], completed in 2018]]\n\nBeecroft helped to found and funds the Beecroft Institute of Particle Physics and Cosmology (BIPAC)<ref name=\":3\" /> at [[Oxford University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.physics.ox.ac.uk/astro/bipac/ |title=Beecroft Institute of Particle Astrophysics and Cosmology |publisher=Physics.ox.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> He has also part-funded the [[Beecroft Building]], part of the [[Department of Physics, University of Oxford|Department of Physics]] in Oxford. This new building is specifically focused on [[Theoretical physics|theoretical]], [[Condensed matter physics|condensed matter]] and [[Quantum (physics)|quantum]] physics. According to ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', the funding for this building was inspired by Beecroft's interest in [[astrophysics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campaign.ox.ac.uk/news/beecroft-building|title=Celebrating the \u2018bottoming out\u2019 of Oxford\u2019s Beecroft Building|website=www.campaign.ox.ac.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nBeecroft has supported his school, Hymer's College in Hull.<ref name=\":3\" />  He has also been a Trustee of Impetus Trust, a social impact charity.<ref name=\":3\" /> Beecroft was also for six years the Chairman of the Cricket Foundation, now known as [[Chance to Shine]], a charity focused on bringing cricket back into British state school education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chancetoshine.org/news/cricket-foundation-elects-donald-brydon-as-new-chairman-of-the-board-of-trustees|title=Cricket Foundation elects Donald Brydon as new Chairman of the Board of Trustees|website=www.chancetoshine.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\nThrough the Beecroft Trust, Adrian and his wife sponsor the [[Oxford Academy, Oxfordshire|Oxford Academy]], an Academy school serving a very deprived area of Oxford.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theoxfordacademy.org.uk/Sponsors|title=Sponsors|website=www.theoxfordacademy.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> Since becoming an Academy school in 2010, its results have improved dramatically from 14% of the students achieving five A* to C grades including English and Maths to 56% achieving this in 2017. However, in 2019 only 17% of pupils achieved grade 5 or above at GCSE and the school had the worst Attainment 8 and Progress 8 scores of any mainstream school in Oxfordshire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/17988398.gcse-2019-results-oxford-academy-disappointed/|title=School 'disappointed' to come bottom in GCSE rankings|website=Oxford Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> In December 2019 the Head and governing body were removed after an [[Ofsted|OFSTED]] inspection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/18090495.head-governors-leave-oxford-academy-ofsted/|title=Mum says school is 'like juvey' as head and governors leave|website=Oxford Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\nMr Beecroft has also supported the [[UNESCO]] initiative to preserve the [[Belize Barrier Reef]] Reserve System, which was classified as in danger on the UNESCO List of World Heritage in Danger in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/1839/|title=Landmark Conservation Action leads to Belize Barrier Reef removal from List of World Heritage in Danger|last=Centre|first=UNESCO World Heritage|website=whc.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>  As of June 2018, the [[World Heritage Committee]] decided to remove the Belize Barrier Reef, which is the world's second largest coral reef, from the list.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-44627719|title=Belize reef taken off 'in danger' list|date=2018-06-27|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Aston Martin DBR1 Adrian Beecroft.jpg|thumb|Adrian Beecroft in his [[Aston Martin DBR1]]]]\nBeecroft lives in [[London]] and supports [[Lord's|Lord's Cricket Ground]] as a [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC) Trustee.<ref name=\":4\">{{Citation|last=Lord's Cricket Ground|title=Meet MCC Trustee Adrian Beecroft {{!}} MCC/Lord's|date=2015-09-29|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QqN_NLDNxVw|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>  As a trustee one of his core roles is assisting with the appointment of the Chairman, but also overseeing the wellbeing of the club and cricket ground.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lords.org/mcc/the-club/mcc-committee/|title=MCC Committee|website=www.lords.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> His enthusiasm for the sport came from watching the [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire County team]] play in Hull.<ref name=\":4\" />  He is the President of Cropredy Cricket Club for whom he still plays league cricket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cropredycc.play-cricket.com/website/player_stats_widget/batting_stats/142168|title=Cropredy CC|website=cropredycc.play-cricket.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\nBeecroft is a supporter of the [[North Yorkshire Moors Railway]] of which he is a Vice-President. He is a keen auto-enthusiast, having an extensive collection of vehicles, including several [[Aston Martin]]s, most notably a [[Aston Martin DBR1|DBR1]] which he races at a number of motoring events and later crashed in 2015.<ref>http://carbuzz.com/m/Article.aspx?Id=29621</ref> He is a governor of [[Hymers College]] in Hull.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commoncat inline|Adrian Beecroft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beecroft, Adrian}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hymers College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The Queen's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Harkness Fellows]]\n[[Category:Angel investors]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) people]]\n", "name_user": "Jpbowen", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrian_Beecroft"}
